U.S.: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, eagerly awaited, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only did the same text use the word "equal as in Iraq" several times, but it did not hesitate to use the title of the Bush declaration of January 2007 for its own statement: "A new road forward."
It was himself, who criticized Bush's idea three years ago to send new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that nothing is talked about today about Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, however objectively left his successor a much more favourable initial situation than he expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
The camp captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the general Afghan operation Stanley McCristal. He, even despite the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided gunmen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president wavered for three months, but nothing better happened to him, so at least he deceived the general over 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him a further 5,000, although he had previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his goal, starting to withdraw Afghanistan's troops in 18 months and ending this procedure in three years. Obama's whole doctrine generated more questions than he offered.
Many doubt that the increase bears the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. After that they will remain patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confused relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capaz de action", a minimum objective of the whole operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is a shock to his volunteerism.
For the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit demonstrated that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians don't know, and they don't want to explain to their constituents what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of developments in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions have no effect on Iranians, the United States will have to make a difficult decision: to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of Afghan troops.
However, each solution will mean a dramatic reversal for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is that there are three years left for the presidential elections and so there is still a lot of time left to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
