Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a matter for employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as it was to impose products on consumers thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end up in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives particularly.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "required that all parties involved (...) should have proactive conduct and a prospective vision"; the BI (Business Intelligence) required an undertaking that was totally opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the collaborators at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative utility
Will internal opinion surveys, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, encourage the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old conductive theory that the American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind them.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a position of mechanical management, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the motivational analysis adopt this conception of employees' motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a default doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
