The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa foundae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1,50 meters high that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an extended head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with hooves and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa findae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues at the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relations, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for the sediments of the Triassic, reports Randall Irmis member of the team of the Utah Natural History Museum.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were assembled in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Many Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander of Bonn University.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the sauries were divided into its three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous teropods among those found in the Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Herbivorous Ornithischia (sauri with bird pelvis), which belong to, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa findsae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also owned by the offspring of the teropods, birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa findae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the teropod with older and primitive air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the parent line of the later giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, researchers conclude that the sauries emerged there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and extended from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earthly mass, the Supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa finds the remains of two other not very closely related teropods.
All three cannot descend from a single parent predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science Study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments Bonn Martin Sander's paleontologist.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils continue to be preserved, while on other continents there is little to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to Mesozoic's dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosauries and many other sauri.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship faded within the boundary of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
Success stories weren't eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
A massive extinction could have been given to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could defeat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slows down the rise of a group of species, which had already evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
