75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey conducted between 9,737 15-75-year-old women leaves no doubt about it: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen job opportunities limited due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation in couples and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have an unstable job, first begin cohabitation as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have less descent.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after commencing living, an increase of 4.1 women with fixed jobs has required more time from their life path to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of their children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a great influence on maternity although less on the timing of the pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and when they have the first vastago.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they marry and at which they have the first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1-32.1 on average, respectively.
"An additional division is established among women according to their level of education.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, middle or upper-level ones reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
