Emergency brake aid is already mandatory
As happened with ABS brake anti-lock and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency brake support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, this is already the case in all new commercial tourism and vehicles, while for the rest there is a period of absence until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians while, in its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency brake assistant is to increase the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the pedestrian the driver gives.
But this doesn't always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car component manufacturer, the third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance the car uses when stopping.
According to an EU study itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided annually.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one out of every four claims will be avoided with damage to people - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects the obstacles and alerts the driver, as well as act slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device shall exert the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
